03586nam a22004815i 9780773565821DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19961996xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735658217 a10.1515/97807735658212doi  a(DE-B1597)657944  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD8039.F6752bC366 1996eb 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a335.4/121 aMuszynski, Alicja, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCheap Wage Labour :bRace and Gender in the Fisheries of British Columbia /cAlicja Muszynski. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1996] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowttledgments -- tIntroduction: The Problematic -- tMarx’s Labour Theory of Value: A Critique -- tPatriarchy and Capitalism -- tThe First Nations, Property Rights, and Salmon Canning -- tThe Dialectics of Cheap Wage Labour -- tOrganized Resistance: The United Fishermen and Allied Workers Union -- tState, Labour, and Capital -- tConclusion: Marx’s Labour Theory of Value Reconsidered -- tAPPENDIX: Labour Classifications, Wage Scales, Conditions of Employment, Board and Accommodation Agreements for Canneries Operated by J.H. Todd & Sons Ltd, 1947-49 -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCheap Wage Labour is the first analysis of shore work and shoreworkers in British Columbia from the 1860s to the mid-1980s. Muszynski provides an interpretation of events that led to the creation of a cheap wage labour force of shoreworkers, their organization within the framework of the fishermen's union (UFAWU), and, as a consequence, the steady decline of their numbers until today they represent only a small portion of the labour force. She looks at factors contributing to the destruction of First Nations culture and economy, such as the displacement of aboriginal peoples from key fishing sites and work in the salmon canneries, and examines the structure and patterns of Chinese and Japanese immigration and the development of the capitalist class and the white working class. Cheap Wage Labour situates the history of B.C. shoreworkers within the much larger and more complex historical enterprise of industrialization, patriarchy, and colonialism and provides keen insights into the current fisheries crisis on the West Coast.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFisherieszBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aFishery processing industrieszBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aLabor theory of valuezBritish ColumbiaxCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356582140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773565821423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773565821/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles